{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510868"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:34:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:34:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11655"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11655"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.05,0.08,0.47,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4276"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41752"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4276"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11655"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26688"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"623"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1393"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5751"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8397"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13901"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41752"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old sheep farmer presents with a one month history of upper abdominal pain. The pain is constant with 6/10 in severity. He denies any history of nausea however he mentioned that he has lost his appetite and is feeling increasingly tired. There are no changes to his bowel movement and he does not notice any blood in his stools. He underwent an anterior resection for carcinoma of the sigmoid colon three years ago. Other past medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. His physical examination is unremarkable. An abdominal ultrasound examination is performed with an abnormality found in the right upper quadrant (image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydatid serology","Endoscopic ultrasound","Percutaneous biopsy","CT chest and abdomen","PET scan"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ultrasound shows multiple solid lesions in the liver which are consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastases. \u003C/strong\u003EThe liver is a common site for metastatic spread.\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003EIn this case, multiple solid liver lesions in the presence of the patient\u0027s history of anorexia, long-standing fatigue, and past diagnosis of sigmoid carcinoma is worrying for metastatic disease. Not all solid liver lesions will be malignant but any incidental solid liver lesion found on ultrasound will require further urgent evaluation. Further imaging is therefore required in this patient to assess the lesions and confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe recommended work-up would be a \u003Cstrong\u003Econtrast CT chest and abdomen. \u003C/strong\u003ECT chest and abdomen may determine a primary disease site; allows staging of known malignant disease; and helps to develop the most appropriate management plan. This is definitely the case here probably in conjunction with some up to date serum tumour markers such as CEA and AFP. A \u003Cstrong\u003EPET\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Escan \u003C/strong\u003Emight be done as further assessment to spot distant metastases, however in this list, CT chest and abdomen is a priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydatid serology\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended to diagnose hydatid cyst which is not the right choice in this case despite the exposure to sheep/farming pathogens. On ultrasound imaging, an hydatid cyst presents as a multiseptated hypoechoic lesion with presence of daughter cysts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous biopsy \u003C/strong\u003Eis not the most appropriate next investigation for this patient. Percutaneous biopsy is an invasive procedure and is required when a histological diagnosis is needed after imaging and staging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic ultrasound \u003C/strong\u003Eis not appropriate. In this particular case, a colonoscopy will be required if not already done for metachronous disease and to assess the surgical site.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Several solid lesions on the liver is consistent with metastatic disease."],"references":["Gome C, Loopez_Andujar R, Ibanez TB, et al. Review of the treatment of liver hydatid cysts World J Gastroenterol 2015; 21:124-31","Neuberger J, Patel J, Caldwell H, Davies S, Hebditch V, Hollywood C, Hubscher S, Karkhanis S, Lester W, Roslund N, West R. Guidelines on the use of liver biopsy in clinical practice from the British Society of Gastroenterology, the Royal College of Radiologists and the Royal College of Pathology. Gut. 2020 Aug 1;69(8):1382-403.","Griscom JT, Wolf PS. Liver Metastasis. InStatPearls [Internet] 2021 Apr 13. StatPearls Publishing.","Schwartz J, Kruskal JB. Approach to the adult patient with an incidental solid liver lesion. UptoDate 2022.  Viewed on January 2023. Accessible via: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/approach-to-the-adult-patient-with-an-incidental-solid-liver-lesion"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26688"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11655"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19362"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19362"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/21793fe2-2984-490d-8cac-ece698135723.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/21793fe2-2984-490d-8cac-ece698135723.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":501,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26688"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-23T07:50:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-06T21:10:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4276"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41752"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"